vegitarian rights at school and home this is something i've been working on for over a year i'm a vegitarian although not truely classified as one since i still eat seafood and chicken chicken was a compromise with my mother anyways i was told repeatedly by my school cafeteria that unless i had a doctor approved diet i could not ask for an exchange of vegitables instead of their stew beef country style steak etc does anyone besides me think this was unfair i just wanted to eat healthier school meat is filled with grease and excersise my rights to a meal btw for anyone who want's to say this isn't healthy my iron level is higher than most who eat meat and being overweight i've lost pounds not that this is a diet it is a lifestyle choice but still its not that i'm trying to take other's rights away just trying to add to my own i'm not the type of person to cry because someone's eating a hamburger in front of me but i think it would be fair for me to be able to enjoy a crisp salad rather than get sloppy joe or some other unidentified meat slapped on my plate here's a packet to help convince your school to offer more veg options http www peta com takecharge pdf vegcafeteria pdf i would go to the head of the cafeteria and the principal and ask your parents to support you on this you shouldn't need a doctor's note in order to eat vegetables if you were indian they would let you have vegetables instead of meat because of your religious convictions it shouldn't be any different with ethical convictions good luck Hamburger Veganism MRE Vegetarianism Japanese cuisine People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals McDonald's Cuisine of Denmark Cuisine of the Southern United States Cuisine of Malaysia German cuisine Dieting Sandwich Cuisine of Laos Barbecue French cuisine Breakfast British cuisine Peruvian cuisine French fries Dim sum Ramen Vegetarianism and religion Vegetarian cuisine Cuisine of Africa Escherichia coli O157:H7 Beef Fish and chips Chili con carne Korean cuisine Om